In another extrinsic case, we test the effect \uncommon{} in a trivia-quiz use case. Similar to the entity summarization experiment, users (in this case players) are shown a list of negations about a concept. However, this time, they havs
e to guess the concept that these negative trivia facts are describing, out of 3 concept. To make it challenging, 2 of the options (i.e., distractors) are chosen from the sibling list of the correct concept-answer. To produce lists of trivia facts, we consider the same methods from Section (ref) and produce top negations for each concept-method pair.